<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-769-306  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 769 306.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Oct 16 1989 v6 n41 p54(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hitachi, Motorola still sparring over RISC chips.andO;(reduced-instruction set computers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnson, Glen.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Hitachi files suit against Motorola, charging that Motorola's88000 reduced-instruction set computing (RISC) microprocessorinfringes on a Hitachi patent.andP;  Motorola says it has no plans tostop production or delivery of the chip.andP;  Motorola is also suingHitachi for allegedly violating patent-license and technologyagreements.andP;  According to Motorola, Hitachi's Zero Turn AroundTime (ZTAT) microprocessors rely on Motorola technology andviolate previous agreements between the two companies.andP;  Hitachihas agreed to phase out the ZTAT microprocessors, but isapparently using Motorola technology in its H-8 products as well.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hitachi Ltd. (cases)Motorola Inc. (cases).andO;Ticker:    MOT.andO;Product:   Motorola 88000 (Microprocessor) (patents).andO;Topic:     Law SuitPatentReduced-Instruction-Set Computers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Hitachi, Motorola Still Sparring over RISC ChipsandM;TARRYTOWN, N.Y.andP;  -- In the latest twist to an ongoing legal battle betweensemiconductor giants Hitachi and Motorola, Hitachi has filed a lawsuitagainst Motorola claiming that Motorola's 88000 microprocessor RISC familyinfringes on Hitachi patents.andM;Specifically, the suit alleges that Motorola's MC88200, a cache/memorymanagement unit, and a member of the 88000 family, infringes on a Hitachipatent.andM;The suit seeks to have Motorola stop any further alleged infringement and payHitachi unspecified damages.andM;Motorola, based in Schaumburg, Ill., refused to comment on the contents ofthe lawsuit.andM;&quot;We'll give our answer in court,&quot; a company spokesman said.andM;The spokesman said he knew of no plans to delay production or delivery of the88000 family because of the suit.andM;Hitachi and Motorola are currently involved in other litigation regardingHitachi's H-8 series of microprocessors.andM;In January, Motorola filed suit against Hitachi and two of its U.S.andO;distributors.andM;One week later, Hitachi filed a counterclaim.andM;According to Motorola, patent-license and related technology agreements thatit had made with Hitachi specifically limited Hitachi's use of Motorola'sconfidential and proprietary information about the MC6800 and MC68000families of microprocessors.andM;Despite that limitation, Motorola claimed that Hitachi introduced its ZeroTurn Around Time (ZTAT) microprocessors in 1986, using Motorola technologythat was excluded from agreements between the companies.andM;Although Hitachi agreed to phase out the ZTAT products by 1990, Motorola'ssuit claimed that last October Hitachi tried again to violate the limitationsspelled out in the companies' agreement by using Motorola technology torender customers dependent on H-8 technology.andM;Motorola is trying to stop the worldwide sale of Hitachi's H-8microprocessors.andM;Hitachi has stated repeatedly that its H-8 products do not infringe upon anyof Motorola's patents and that those microprocessors are licensed under theagreement between the two manufacturers.andM;Hitachi's counterclaim against Motorola alleged that Motorola infringed on aHitachi patent in developing Motorola's 68HC11 microprocessor.andM;Hitachi later dropped that suit.andM;In June, Hitachi filed a second suit against Motorola, claiming Motorola'sMC68030 infringes on a Hitachi patent.andP;  Motorola has denied the allegation.andM;A trial encompassing each of the companies' suits and counterclaims isscheduled to begin later this month in Austin, Texas.andO;</TEXT></DOC>